task.summary: Default task
hello vau.
parse vau expressions to lists, numbers, and symbols
catch more syntax errors
parse floats as well as ints
the very basics of eval
eval of 'quote', 'if', 'define', and proc application of builtin procs
more python operators added to the environment (in a very un-vau way)
evau: the ultimate pun
define set! and fn (lambda)
define vau. It works in that it doesn't evaluate its arguments, but there is currently not much you can do with it because there isn't any access to the environment.
use a real repl. define 'unquote' so that vau can make fexpr-like things.
early version of defsyntax (allows a syntax form with one placeholder at the end)
define $platform-object with .` syntaxitive. Allows access to builtins, which in turn allows module loading

treat dict objects as functions of their keys
Note that (some-dict 'foo) => 'bar but (some-dict 'foo 'baz) => ('bar 'frob)
start to autocomplete functionality and more reflection
data driven declaration and handling of evau for builtins
be struct about level-0 symbol name encodings
it's called "prelude", not "prologue"
define @evau and @get-current-environment
define $vau correctly; take the meaning of the word "applicative" seriously for @eval, ignore _ symbols
don't refer to environment in $quote when we aren't going to use it
be more strict about symbol usage
start of lexical macros (define a symbol with a '^' prefix and it can be evaluated at read-time when the reader sees that symbol without the '^' prefix at the beginning of a list)
get-current-environment doesn't need to be builtin
define rem macro for comments in the prelude
lost the symbol prefixes for non-syntaxitives and unify defsyntax! for reader macros and eval macros
define doesn't need an exclamation mark (because it introduces a new symbol rather than mutating it), but defsyntax! does (because it mutates the reader as it is running)
allow forms to span multiple lines in a file; get rid of Applicative and lose the builtin lambda (will be defined in the language soon)
lambda: the penultimate abstraction (lambda is now defined in vau)

call platform-object "python-object" to avoid premature abstraction
- it doesn't make sense to abstract multi-platformness before we have another platform (we won't even know what we need)
- python-object needs to explicitly check if it's callable and raw-wrap it if it is
defun: in which I start to become enlightened

defun: in which I start to become enlightened
I'm pretty sure every lisp geek has a story about when they became enlightened. This is mine.
So here's the interesting thing about lisp enlightenment: you always think it's already happened. In my case, I've been studying and playing with various lisps off and on for years now. I understand code-as-data and I understand how homoiconicity helps that along. When I say I understand it I mean that I know about it and I can tell you why it's important and the kind of things it lets you do. But today was the first day that I *felt* it.
What did it take to become enlightened? Struggling with errors. I was trying to add "defun" to the prelude. It kept not working. I really wished I had a debugger so I could see what lisp was doing. But then I realized: I DO have a debugger. The REPL is right there! So I just kept building up a list in the repl using the list and quote operators and hitting the up arrow and editing it until I had about what I wanted. Then, when I thought it looked good, I "evau"d it. I was able to build up code incrementally, programmatically, until it took the form I wanted. Then I was able to build a function that spit out that code. Then I wrapped that in a define. And then I was done.
Am I fully enlightened? No. But I'm really starting to get it.

cond: it's nicer the Arc way
cond or if, which is primitive? I think I prefer cond because it's more "normal". if feels ad-hoc as a primitive. I chose to implement the Arc version of cond (without the implicit progn/do block). I think pg's rationale (in "Arc at 3 weeks") is sound.

lambda is an onion
Can you tell I've been reading some Paul Graham? I think he's right about lambda. It's an onion and is used far too often to have such a long name. Also, it's nice to have a two-letter name for fn when vau is a three letter name.
Now I just have to figure out what to do with define.

(:: define ::)
This introduces the "::" operator, which should be read "as" or "is now". This unifies some previously ad-hoc syntax. For example, now let can be a binding while "let::" says "this is NOW a binding (that will persist)". Now we don't need set.
This is most clear in the "fn" case. "fn" IS a function, "fn::" says "this is NOW a function (with a name that will persist)".
